h3. Issue Summary

Cannot edit certain pages, with different errors for pages that use different editors:
 * New Editor (Fabric):
{quote}(!) *Can't save changes*
 Your internet is playing up. Please check your connection and refresh.
{quote}
!Screenshot 2019-11-13 at 12.43.38.png|width=384,height=155!

 * Old Editor (TinyMCE):
{quote}(!)*The connection timed out*
 Check you can connect to the internet, then try reloading. If there's no problem with your connection, speak to your Confluence admin.
{quote}
  !Screenshot 2019-11-13 at 12.42.45.png|width=480,height=224!

h3. Steps to Reproduce
* N/A. Happens on random pages

h3. Expected Results
* Able to edit pages and publish

h3. Actual Results
* Cannot publish changes

The below error can be found when checking browser's developer tools:-

For old editor pages:
{{500}} response for {{https://wikidocs.services.atlassian.com/v1/data/-xxxxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx/confluence-xxxx?state-at=@head&state-format=type-tagged&rewrite-request=true&cached=true}}:
{noformat}
{"message":"Internal Server Error","id":"XxFH18JVz8EnkO9qEnmnUg"}
{noformat}

For new editor pages:
{{500}} response for {{https://wikidocs.services.atlassian.com/v1/data/<sitename>--xxxxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx/confluence-adf-xxxx?state-at=@head&state-format=adf-container&rewrite-request=true&cached=true}}:
{noformat}
{"message":"Internal Server Error","id":"y0RSWn00y-rppjhWnd727Q"}
{noformat}

and

{{500}} response for {{https://wikidocs.services.atlassian.com/v1/data/<sitename>--xxxxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx/confluence-adf-xxxx?optimistic=true&rewrite-request=true}}:
{noformat}
{"message":"Internal Server Error","id":"3w40TMjWjy8jx7_lsoZiOQ"}
{noformat}

h3. Workaround

Make a copy of the affected pages, and you should be able to edit the new copy. You may choose to keep the affected page for support investigation, or remove it and rename your copy to the original page name.

h3. Issue Summary

Deleting an attachment (e.g. .xlsx file) that was dragged and dropped into an expand macro fails - When clicking the *x* sign on the bottom of the attachment
h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Insert an expand macro into a page;
# Drag & drop a file into the macro;
# Publish the page;
# Edit the page again and click on the *x* under the file

h3. Expected Results
* File to be removed from the page

h3. Actual Results
* The file fails to be deleted, no error is displayed;
* Sometimes clicking more than once on the *x* button removes the file;

h3. Workaround
* Select the file like regular text and hit delete on the keyboard, or by using backspace until the image is deleted;

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-59102].
  {panel}

Request for inclusion of the new Chromium based [Microsoft Edge|https://www.microsoftedgeinsider.com/en-us/] in Confluence supported platform.

h3. Issue Summary
If we copy a table that is set as full-width or wide to inside an *Expand* macro, no matter which width you select to the Expand, it will get the width from the table.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a page in the new editing experience;
# Add a table and set it to wide;
# Insert and *Expand* macro;
# Copy the table to within the Expand;
# Delete the table that is out from the expand;
# For comparing purposes, add another Expand macro;
# From within the new Expand, add a table;
# Publish the page

h3. Expected Results
Both Expand macros are aligned in the same way.

h3. Actual Results
The first Expand is left-aligned, comparing the other one.

h3. Workaround
# Cut the table from within the expand macro;
# Paste it into the page;
# Change the table width to *center*;
# Cut the table from the editor;
# Paste it back to the Expand.

h3. Issue Summary
If we select an image and copy it from the editing mode of a template and try to paste this image on a second template, all the changes we did on the second template will not save after saving the template.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a template called *Template A* and insert an image from an existing page;
# Save the *Template A*;
# Create a new template called *Template B*;
# Insert some text content on this template and save it;
# Open the editing mode of the *Template A* on a new tab;
# Open the editing mode of the *Template B* on a different tab;
# From the *Template A*, select and copy the image;
# Paste it into the *Template B*;
# Add some additional text content in the *Template B* and save it;
# Edit the *Template B*.

h3. Expected Results
The additional text content we inserted is there, but the image - as it is not possible to attach files on a template.

h3. Actual Results
All the changes are gone.

*Notes*:
* It is known that images and files cannot be directly attached to a template, but the rest of the content should be at least saved instead of getting whipped out;
* If you took a screenshot and paste it into *Template B*, after saving it and reopening it will come with a *Broken Image* thumbnail - better than have the additional content whipped out;
* It is not an issue on the new editing experience, once it is not possible to attach any files on templates.

h3. Workaround
Use the *Insert Files and Images* button from the toolbar in order to add images on templates when using the old editor

h3. Issue Summary
When using the *Excerpt Include* macro on a new editing experience page, it is not possible to hide the panel around the excerpted content selecting the *Remove Surrounding Panel* option in the macro settings.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a new page called *Page A* and add the *Excerpt* macro;
# Add some content within the macro and publish the page;
# Create a new page called *Page B*;
# Insert the *Excerpt Include* macro;
# Fill the page field with *Page A* title;
# Mark the checkbox *Remove Surrounding Panel*;
# Save the macro and publish the page.

h3. Expected Results
The panel around the excerpted content is gone, showing only the content.

h3. Actual Results
The panel is still there.

*Notes*:
* If you back to edit *Page B* and check the macro settings, the mark box is like if was never checked.

h3. Workaround
To avoid running into this issue, add a new Excerpt Include macro, and select *Remove Surrounding Panel* as soon as you insert the macro. (However, there's a catch, once you add this option you'd be unable to toggle it off/on again)

h3. Issue Summary
When creating a new template with the new editing experience, if we add a template variable into a table, all the other template variables after the first added (or even existing ones) will vanish.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a new template;
# Add a table;
# Add a template variable and name it as *1*;
# Add a second, third, or fourth template variable with different names, inside or outside the table;
# Save the template;
# Create a new page with the template or edit the template.

h3. Expected Results
Al the template variables are there to be filled with your information.

h3. Actual Results
Only the first variable you added in the table is there D:

h3. Workaround
Avoid to insert the template variable inside a table.

h3. Summary
When editing a template (page blueprint) with [the new editor|https://support.atlassian.com/confluence-cloud/docs/learn-about-confluence-cloud-editing-improvements/], it's not possible to [change its width|https://community.atlassian.com/t5/Confluence-discussions/Full-width-mode-is-now-available-for-the-new-editor-in/td-p/1138727] as it's possible in the editor for existing and new pages.

h3. Suggestion
This is a suggestion to implement the option to change the page's width of the editor for templates as well.

h3. Workaround
Set the width after creating a new page with the template. Alternatively, you can enable full-width as the default for new pages, which would make the pages created from templates to already use it. To do so, follow the steps below:

# Tap your profile picture and select *Settings* (bottom of the sidebar or top-right for the [new navigation|https://support.atlassian.com/confluence-cloud/docs/improved-confluence-navigation/]);
# Select *Editor* and click on *Edit*;
# Check the *Enable full-width as the default for new pages* option;
# Tap *Submit*;
